100 km2. No country has fewer than 29 threatened species within its Exclusive Economic Zone. This substantial change in species richness patterns over the past half-century is due to the local extinction of thirteen species from signi\ufb01 cant parts of the range (Figure 6). Geographically, local extinctions have been most prevalent in the NW Mediterranean waters of Spain, France, and Italy, and in the waters of the countries bordering the Adriatic Sea and northwest African countries. > THE PRINCIPAL DRIVER OF DECLINE AND LOCAL EXTINCTION IS OVERFISHING.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "575df7cf-75f5-4bb2-8b38-1fd6c8caac6f": {"__data__": {"id_": "575df7cf-75f5-4bb2-8b38-1fd6c8caac6f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/conservation-status-sharks-rays-and-chimaeras-mediterranean-sea", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The conservation status of sharks, rays, and chimaeras in the Mediterranean Sea", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/conservation-status-sharks-rays-and-chimaeras-mediterranean-sea", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1cdb4421b5599d7339ff15078a21b7939bedd5e4646a13e6ab47159a1eb61690"}, "2": {"node_id": "99cb68ad-b50e-4b5f-8db8-c28586d2fc3f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/conservation-status-sharks-rays-and-chimaeras-mediterranean-sea", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher":